\begin_layout Standard
The household attempts to maximize the utility function, given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{j=0}^{\infty}\frac{U(C_{t+j})}{(1+\rho)^{j}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The current budget constraint is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}+T_{t}+t_{t-1}B_{t}-C_{t}=B_{t+1}-B_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Saving equals income minus consumption, which equals the increase in assets).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inter-temporal budget constraint is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{t}+T_{t}-C_{t}+\frac{Y_{t+1}+T_{t+1}-C_{t+1}}{1+r_{t}}+\cdots+(1+r_{t-1})B_{t}=0
\]

\end_inset

Or:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
PV_{t}(Y+T-C)+(1+r_{t-1})B_{t}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using Langrangian, The Euler equation interpretation gives:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U_{c}(C_{t})=\frac{1+r_{t}}{1+\rho}U_{c}(C_{t+1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $U(C_{t})=ln(C_{t})$
\end_inset

, we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t+1}=\frac{1+r_{t}}{1+\rho}C_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}=\rho$
\end_inset

, consumption would be constant (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smoothing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - the return equals the cost of waiting).
\end_layout

