\begin_layout Subsection
The Permanent-Income Hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Milton Friedman, rephrase in a modern version: Money spending is consistent
 with the expected long-term income.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}=r_{t+1}=\rho$
\end_inset

.
 The Euler equation implies 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smoothing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of consumption:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{C_{t}}=\frac{1}{C_{t+1}}\frac{1+r}{1+\rho}\Rightarrow C_{t}=C_{t+1}=C_{t+2}=\ldots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Does it imply equal consumption over time? 
\series bold
No
\series default
.
 Computation of 
\series bold
Permanent income
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y^{P}$
\end_inset

 - the budget constaint can be written as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t}\left[1+\frac{1}{1+r}+\frac{1}{(1+r)^{2}}+\cdots\right]=PV_{t}(Y+T)+(1+r)B_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\series bold

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{t}=\frac{r}{1+r}[PV_{t}(Y+T)+(1+r)B_{t}]=Y_{t}^{P}+rB_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The optimal consumption is to consume the interest on future income, plus
 the interest on previous savings
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, it 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}=Y,\,T_{t}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{t}=0$
\end_inset

, then:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
PV_{t}(Y)=Y\left[1+\frac{1}{1+r}+\frac{1}{(1+r)^{2}}+\cdots\right]=Y\frac{1+r}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\frac{r}{1+r}Y\frac{1+r}{r}=Y=Y^{P}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 goes up permanently, the consumption increases by the same delta.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If it increases temporary by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

, the effect on the consumption would be: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{r}{1+r}\Theta$
\end_inset


\end_layout

